    body: "The VA Aid and Attendance benefit is a monthly pension supplement paid by the Department of Veterans Affairs to wartime veterans and surviving spouses who need help with daily activities like bathing, dressing, eating, or moving around the house. As of May 2026, the maximum monthly Aid and Attendance payment for a single veteran is $2,358, for a married veteran is $2,795, and for a surviving spouse is $1,515. These are tax-free dollars that arrive in your bank account each month, on top of any other VA pension you may already receive. About 9 million American veterans are age 65 or older, and the VA estimates that more than 230,000 of them are missing out on Aid and Attendance because they do not know it exists.\n\nTo qualify for Aid and Attendance, a veteran must have served at least 90 days of active duty, with at least one day during a wartime period. Wartime periods include World War II, the Korean War, the Vietnam War, the Gulf War, and the period after September 11, 2001. The veteran must also have been honorably discharged. The income and asset limits change every year; for 2026, a single veteran can have up to $159,240 in countable assets, not including the home you live in or one vehicle. The veteran must also need help with at least two activities of daily living, or be bedridden, or live in a nursing home, or have very poor eyesight.\n\nThe application is paperwork-heavy, but with a written checklist it can be done in one afternoon. The VA does not charge a fee to apply, and you do not need a lawyer or a paid consultant. Many for-profit companies advertise help with Aid and Attendance for fees of $500 to several thousand dollars; do not pay them. Free, accredited help is available from your state Veterans Service Officer, the American Legion, the Veterans of Foreign Wars, Disabled American Veterans, or your local county Veterans Affairs office. These groups are trained to walk you through the paperwork at no cost.\n\nBefore you begin, gather your DD-214 discharge papers, your marriage certificate if you are married or a surviving spouse, your spouse's death certificate if applicable, the last three months of bank statements, the last year of medical bills, and a doctor's letter describing the help you need. Set aside a quiet morning. Have a folder ready for organizing copies. If you do not have a computer, you can apply by paper mail; if you do have a computer, the online application is faster. The whole process from application to first payment usually takes four to six months in 2026.",
