    body: "When a senior veteran needs full-time care that families can no longer provide at home, the Department of Veterans Affairs offers three main paths to nursing home care: VA-owned Community Living Centers, state Veterans Homes run by individual states with VA funding, and community nursing homes that contract with the VA. As of May 2026, the VA pays for some or all nursing home care for veterans who meet specific eligibility rules, and more than 130,000 veterans are receiving paid long-term care under VA programs. Choosing the right nursing home is one of the biggest decisions a family can make, and the VA system has rules that differ from regular Medicare or Medicaid coverage.\n\nFirst, eligibility. The VA pays for nursing home care if the veteran has a service-connected disability rated 70 percent or higher, or if the veteran requires care because of a service-connected condition regardless of rating, or if the veteran has been determined to need nursing home care based on a clinical assessment and meets financial rules. Surviving spouses are generally not eligible for VA nursing home payment unless the veteran already had a paid placement before death. Aid and Attendance pension, covered in our separate guide, can also help pay for private nursing home care for eligible veterans and surviving spouses.\n\nThe three VA paths each have strengths and weaknesses. Community Living Centers, run directly by the VA, offer the deepest integration with VA medical care but have limited beds and waiting lists in many states. State Veterans Homes, run by state governments with federal funding, often have more beds and may accept veterans whose service connection is lower than 70 percent; quality varies widely by state and individual home. Community nursing homes give the most choice in location but require the VA to approve each individual placement and review it every six months. All three options must meet federal nursing home quality standards.\n\nBefore you begin, set aside a week or two for the search. Have ready the veteran's DD-214 discharge papers, current VA enrollment status, any recent medical records, and a list of family members willing to visit candidate homes in person. Plan to visit at least three facilities before making a decision. Bring a notebook to each visit; first impressions fade quickly. If the veteran has a VA case manager, primary care doctor, or social worker, contact them early in the process because their referral can speed approval. The whole process from first search to admission usually takes three to eight weeks for a community placement, longer for a VA Community Living Center.",
