    body: "VA dental benefits are one of the most misunderstood areas of veterans benefits. Many senior veterans believe their VA health care includes free dental care, only to find out at a painful tooth visit that dental is mostly separate. As of May 2026, fewer than 1 in 6 enrolled VA patients qualify for full free VA dental care. The other veterans have two options: pay out of pocket at private dentists, or enroll in the VA Dental Insurance Program, known as VADIP, which is a low-cost insurance plan available through Delta Dental or MetLife and underwritten with VA oversight. Understanding which category you fall into is the first step.\n\nFull free VA dental care, called Class I or Class II eligibility, is available to veterans with a service-connected dental condition rated as compensable, former prisoners of war, totally and permanently disabled veterans with service-connected ratings, veterans recently discharged with documented dental needs at separation, and certain other narrow categories. Full free care covers cleanings, fillings, extractions, root canals, dentures, and most dental work, all at a VA dental clinic at no charge. Patients in these categories can call the VA dental clinic at their nearest VA Medical Center to schedule.\n\nVADIP, by contrast, is available to any veteran enrolled in VA health care, plus CHAMPVA beneficiaries and certain surviving spouses. Premiums in 2026 range from about $13 per month for a basic plan to $55 per month for a comprehensive plan, depending on your state and the carrier you choose. VADIP covers preventive care like cleanings and exams at lower out-of-pocket cost than buying private dental insurance on the open market, and most plans have no waiting period for preventive care. Annual maximum coverage varies by plan, often $1,000 to $3,500 per year. VADIP plans are nationwide and you can choose any participating dentist.\n\nBefore you begin, gather your VA enrollment information, your VA identification card if you have one, and a list of any dental work you know you need. Set aside an hour to research and compare plans. The VADIP enrollment can be done online at va.gov, by phone with the carriers directly, or by mail. Annual open enrollment for VADIP runs in November and December for the following year, but you can enroll anytime if you have a qualifying life event like a new VA enrollment, a move, or the loss of other dental coverage. Once enrolled, the coverage begins on the first day of the month after enrollment.",
