    body: "Free mental health care is one of the most generous and least-used benefits the Department of Veterans Affairs offers. Any veteran with an other-than-dishonorable discharge can receive VA mental health services, regardless of service-connected rating, regardless of income, and regardless of when or where they served. As of May 2026, the VA employs more than 27,000 mental health professionals across 1,300 sites, including primary care clinics, mental health clinics, Vet Centers, and a 24-hour Crisis Line. Services include individual therapy, group therapy, marriage counseling, medication management, and specialized care for post-traumatic stress, depression, grief, and substance use.\n\nMany senior veterans grew up at a time when mental health was a private topic, not something you discussed openly. That generation often carries the heavy burden of decades-old combat memories, grief from losing friends, or the lonely weight of being the last surviving member of an old unit. The good news is that the VA has invested heavily in age-appropriate mental health care for older veterans, including therapies designed for late-life grief, end-of-life concerns, and the kind of regrets that can quietly take over the years after retirement. Talking with a trained counselor is not a sign of weakness; it is a sign of taking care of yourself the same way you would for a sore knee or a heart concern.\n\nThere are five ways into VA mental health care, each suited to a different need. The fastest, for any veteran in crisis, is the Veterans Crisis Line at 988 then Press 1, available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. The next is walking into a Vet Center, which is a smaller, less formal counseling center separate from VA Medical Centers, with locations in most cities. The third is asking your VA primary care doctor for a mental health referral, often called Primary Care Mental Health Integration, which is the most common path. The fourth is calling the VA mental health intake line at 877-222-8387. The fifth is using the My HealtheVet portal to send a secure message to your primary care team.\n\nBefore you begin, take a moment to think about what kind of help fits your situation. If you are in crisis with thoughts of harming yourself or others, stop reading and call 988 right now, then press 1 to reach the Veterans Crisis Line. If you are dealing with sadness, anxiety, grief, sleep problems, anger, or memories that will not stop replaying, any of the non-crisis paths below will get you to a counselor within one to four weeks. Have your VA enrollment status ready. If you have never enrolled in VA health care, you can still get help at a Vet Center without enrolling first, because Vet Centers operate under a different rule than VA Medical Centers.",
